This unique and hard to find firearm is the ultimate setup for home defense.  It is being tested and adopted by US Special Forces as the ideal close quarters weapon.

Check out this feature article in the current edition of Guns & Ammo on this weapon (same setup, but from a different manufacturer – the DD is not yet released, this is available today!)

This AR15 is a CMMG 12.5” chambered in 300 Blackout.  It is the ideal home defense firearm because:

•	It has a 30 caliber bullet.  More potent than the standard AR (.223 or 5.56).
•	It has ideal ballistics in a Short Barrel Weapon.  Standard AR needs a longer barrel to achieve ideal ballistics.
•	It is designed to run subsonic or supersonic ammo.  What’s the point of a home defense weapon that if used renders everyone deaf afterwards?  This is one of the main reasons I have switched to the 300 Blackout.
•	It is also legal to hunt with in Colorado.  You can’t hunt with a standard AR.

300 Blackout only needs a different barrel.  Other than that, it uses all the standard AR parts.  Magazine, bolt, everything is standard.

A standard AR  has a 16” barrel, which is longer than ideal for home defense.  You can get a Short Barrel Rifle (SBR), but you need to apply to the ATF, pay $200 for a stamp and wait 4-8 months for approval.

This AR lower is registered as a pistol.   If you want to make it a rifle, you just need to apply, but this means you can legally use it immediately as-is.

What is 300 Blackout?

From Wikipedia:
Since its inception, as the standard US military primary issue rifle ammunition, the 5.56×45mm NATO round has run up against firm opposition from those who argue that the 30 caliber round provides the minimum, if not ideal, performance necessary for the modern battlefield soldier. While 5.56mm NATO has enjoyed widespread acceptance in military circles, the fluid nature of the missions that some special operations groups encounter often demand a round that not only provides better performance[1] than that available in the high energy standard velocity rounds but also one that can offer subsonic performance greater than the current standard 9mm submachine guns now in use.

title: For Sale:  FEG SMC-380
postcontent:
Sale Includes: Pistol, 2 standard 7-round magazines, 1 8-round magazine, De-Santis leather holster, original box with paperwork.

FEG model SMC-380 da/sa pistol in 380 acp caliber. A copy of the Walther PPK. Blue finish, alloy frame, 3.5" barrel, plastic grips with thumbrest. 

The SMC-380 is of historical interest because it is the smallest gun ever imported legally into the U.S. since the passage of the Gun Control Act of 1968 (according to which a gun cannot be imported if it is less than 4.0 inches in height). The SMC-380, which is barely 4.1 inches high, had to have a target-type left grip installed to meet the government's stringent importation criteria. The left target-style grip widened the pistol from 1.1 to 1.3 inches, but that was a small price to pay. A thinner, flatter left grip panel is also available on request.

Like the PMK-380, the SMC-380 is available only in .380 ACP caliber. Its alloy frame makes it smoother and two or three ounces lighter than the PPK. It also carries better in a pocket than the higher-priced German gun and it fits the average hand better. Its sights, while tiny, are easy to line up quickly, thanks to the comfortable curve of the backstrap. In testing an early SMC-380, the pistol proved quite accurate.
